<h3><u>Switch Statements</h3></u>
<p>The switch statement is used to select one code block to execute from a large number of code blocks</p>
<p>Syntax:</p><b><i>switch(expression) {<br>
  case x:<br>
    // code block<br>
    break;<br>
  case y:<br>
    // code block<br>
    break;<br>
  default:<br>
    // code block<br>
}</b></i><br><br>
<u>break Keyword</u>
<p>C++ breaks out of the switch block when it reaches a break keyword</p>
<u>default keyword</u>
<p>The code inside the default code block will run if no match can be found</p>
<p>For Example:</p>int day = 4;<br>
switch (day) {<br>
  case 6:<br>
    cout << "Today is Saturday";<br>
    break;<br>
  case 7:<br>
    cout << "Today is Sunday";<br>
    break;<br>
  default:<br>
    cout << "Looking forward to the Weekend";<br>
}<br><b>Output:</b><br>Looking forward to the Weekend<br>

<p>Example 2:</p>int day = 4;<br>
switch (day) {<br>
  case 1:<br>
    cout << "Monday";<br>
    break;<br>
  case 2:<br>
    cout << "Tuesday";<br>
    break;<br>
  case 3:<br>
    cout << "Wednesday";<br>
    break;<br>
  case 4:<br>
    cout << "Thursday";<br>
    break;<br>
  case 5:<br>
    cout << "Friday";<br>
    break;<br>
  case 6:<br>
    cout << "Saturday";<br>
    break;<br>
  case 7:<br>
    cout << "Sunday";<br>
    break;<br>
}<br><b>Output:</b><br>Thursday<br>

